***Abstract*****—We seek a method to enhance fire detection. There are many ways to perform fire detection, such as human intervention, infrared, and other methods, but they are often lacking in either speed or quality. Using a You Only Look Once model version 8 (YOLO**v8) **as our model of choice, we demonstrate the effectiveness of the model that was trained to detect fire and the smoke from the burning. Though the YOLO**v8 **model needs a diverse set of images of fire and smoke, we demonstrate how well using the YOLOv8 model and object detection framework works and how accurately YOLOv8 can determine fires and smoke. We also demonstrate how fast and accurately it can be done when applied to video with real-time feedback. The demonstration shows a potential use that can be run in real time, which may be useful in alerting to potential fire before it gets out of control, with better situational awareness and reaction than other methods.**

***Keywords—YOLOv8, PyTorch, , YAML, classification***

2. # Methods

   1. ## *Data Preparation*

     To ensure the robustness and adaptability of the YOLOv8 model across varied detection scenarios, a comprehensive data preparation strategy was implemented. The dataset annotations adhere to the YOLOv5 PyTorch specification, where each object instance is represented by a single line in a text file. Each line consists of the class label followed by the normalized bounding box parameters — namely, center\_x, center\_y, width, and height — relative to the image dimensions. These annotation files are managed in conjunction with a YAML configuration that specifies dataset paths and class names.

     Advanced data augmentation techniques were employed to enhance the model’s generalization capabilities. YOLOv8 utilizes mosaic augmentation, which combines four distinct images into a single composite input, and mixup augmentation, which blends two images and their associated labels. These strategies allow the model to encounter a diverse range of object sizes, orientations, and spatial distributions during training, significantly improving its performance on small or partially occluded objects.

2. ## *Model Architecture*

     The YOLOv8 detection model is designed as a unified, end-to-end neural network architecture optimized for both speed and accuracy. It consists of three major components: the Backbone, the Neck, and the Head.  
     The Backbone is derived from an advanced version of the CSPDarknet architecture, engineered for efficient hierarchical feature extraction. It employs depthwise separable convolutions and layer aggregation techniques to reduce redundancy while maintaining high representational capacity.  
     The Neck integrates a Feature Pyramid Network (FPN) with an enhanced Path Aggregation Network (PANet) to facilitate multi-scale feature fusion. This component ensures that both low-level texture details and high-level semantic cues are preserved and aggregated across scales for more accurate object detection.  
     The Head of YOLOv8 is distinguished by its anchor-free detection mechanism, which eliminates the dependency on predefined anchor boxes used in earlier YOLO variants. This approach simplifies training, reduces hyperparameter tuning, and improves adaptability to objects with varying aspect ratios.  
     Additionally, YOLOv8 offers scalable architecture variants—Nano (n), Small (s), Medium (m), Large (l), and Extra-Large (x)—to support deployment across edge devices, mobile platforms, and high-performance servers.

4. ## *Training Strategy*

The Real-Time Fire and Smoke Detection model, leveraging the high-speed YOLOv8 Nano architecture, was trained on a custom dataset of 15,068 images for 50 epochs using pre-trained weights. Optimization was handled by Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) with an initial learning rate (lr0) of 0.01 and a momentum of 0.9. A consistent batch size of 16 and standard data augmentation techniques (such as Mosaic and random Fliplr) were applied. The training utilized an NVIDIA Tesla T4 GPU, completing the 50 epochs in approximately 3.355 hours, with efficiency further enhanced by the use of Automatic Mixed Precision (AMP). The process successfully minimized the complex Box, Classification, and Distribution Focal Loss components, resulting in a converged model ready for evaluation.

3. # Experimental Setup.

   1. ## *Data Preprocessing*

The dataset used in this project was sourced from Roboflow and consists of approximately **4,000 labeled images** containing instances of *fire*, *smoke*, or background scenes. These images were collected from a variety of aerial and ground-level perspectives to capture differing viewpoints, environmental conditions, and camera qualities. To prepare the data for YOLOv8, all images were standardized to a resolution of **256×256 pixels**, ensuring consistent input dimensions across training and inference.

Each image is paired with a YOLO-formatted annotation file in which every bounding box is represented as:

\[class\_id, x\_center, y\_center, width, height\]\[class\\\_id,\\ x\\\_center,\\ y\\\_center,\\ width,\\ height\]\[class\_id, x\_center, y\_center, width, height\]

All coordinates were normalized to a \[0,1\]\[0,1\]\[0,1\] range relative to the image dimensions, providing scale-invariant representations suitable for object detection models.

To enhance model robustness, YOLOv8’s built-in data augmentation pipeline was enabled during training. This included random flipping, mosaic augmentation, cropping, and brightness/contrast jitter. These augmentations simulate real wildfire conditions such as variable lighting, partial occlusion, varying flame shapes, and smoke density fluctuations, ultimately allowing the model to generalize more effectively to unseen fire scenarios.

2. ## *Data Splitting Strategy*

To evaluate model performance fairly and avoid overfitting, the dataset was partitioned into **training**, **validation**, and **test** subsets. A statistically standard split of **80% training**, **10% validation**, and **10% testing** was used. The split was performed randomly while maintaining class balance to ensure that both *fire* and *smoke* samples were proportionally represented in each subset.

* **Training Set (80%)** – Used for parameter optimization during YOLOv8 training.

* **Validation Set (10%)** – Used to tune hyperparameters and monitor convergence.

* **Test Set (10%)** – Held out entirely for final evaluation to assess generalization.

The dataset configuration, including image paths and class names, was specified in the project's **fire\_detect.yaml** file. YOLOv8 uses this configuration to automatically load images, parse normalized bounding-box annotations, and construct batches for end-to-end training.

This splitting strategy ensures that the final performance metrics—such as precision, recall, mAP, and inference speed—represent the model’s true ability to detect fire and smoke in previously unseen imagery.

3. ## *Model Architecture*

The core of this real-time detection system is the YOLOv8 Nano (YOLOv8n) model. The Nano variant was selected specifically to achieve the high inference speeds necessary for live video stream processing, while maintaining robust detection capability for the two target classes: 'Fire' and 'Smoke'. The architecture follows the standard three-component structure common to modern one-stage detectors, but introduces key optimizations relative to prior YOLO versions:

1. Backbone  
   The backbone is responsible for extracting rich, multi-scale features from the input image. In YOLOv8, this convolutional network utilizes a modernized structure: 

* C2f Module: The traditional C3 module is replaced by the C2f (Cross-Stage Partial layer with two convolution blocks) module. This design enhances gradient flow and improves feature reuse efficiency, contributing significantly to both model accuracy and reduced parameter count.  
* Feature Maps: The backbone outputs feature maps at three distinct scales (P3, P4, P5), which are then passed to the neck for fusion, ensuring the model can detect objects ranging from small, distant smoke plumes to large, close-up fires.

   

2. Neck (Feature Aggregation).

   The neck component is crucial for integrating multi-scale features, allowing the model to leverage both high-level semantic information (from deep layers) and low-level spatial information (from shallow layers).

* PANet/FPN Structure: The neck employs a fusion structure based on a Path Aggregation Network (PANet) augmented with a Feature Pyramid Network (FPN). This dual-path network allows information to flow both top-down and bottom-up, generating high-quality feature maps for the detection head.   
* SPPF Layer: A Spatial Pyramid Pooling \- Fast (SPPF) layer is incorporated at the end of the backbone. This accelerates feature fusion by conducting pooling operations on multiple kernel sizes sequentially, effectively increasing the receptive field without adding significant computational overhead.  
3. Detection Head

   YOLOv8 introduced significant updates to the prediction mechanism, enhancing localization and classification performance:

* Decoupled Head: Unlike earlier single-branch heads, YOLOv8 utilizes a decoupled head, separating the classification task (What is it: Fire/Smoke?) from the bounding box regression task (Where is it?). This improves the model's ability to learn complex feature representations for each task independently.   
* Anchor-Free Detection: The model predicts object centers directly rather than relying on pre-defined anchor boxes. This simplifies the prediction mechanism, reduces the number of heuristic hyperparameters, and aids in better generalization across varied object shapes, which is critical for detecting amorphous objects like fire and smoke.

The resultant YOLOv8n model is a compact network of 225 layers with a total of 3,006,038 fused parameters, providing the necessary architectural depth for the detection task while ensuring efficiency.

4. ## *Loss Function and Training*

The training of the YOLOv8n model is driven by a composite loss function to optimize both localization and classification simultaneously. The total loss is comprised of three parts: a Bounding Box Loss (utilizing CIoU/DIoU for regression quality), a Classification Loss (VFL/BCE), and the Distribution Focal Loss (DFL). DFL is unique to YOLOv8's anchor-free head, explicitly minimizing the distance between the predicted and target box representations, ensuring precise bounding box localization. This multi-component loss strategy, coupled with a Task-Aligned Assigner for selecting positive training samples, is key to the model's robust performance.

5. ## *Evaluation Metrics and Hyperparameters*

Model performance was assessed using standard object detection metrics derived from the validation set. The primary metric is the Mean Average Precision (mAP). Specifically, we report mAP@0.5 (the average precision calculated at an Intersection over Union (IoU) threshold of 0.5) and mAP@0.5:0.95 (the mean mAP across IoU thresholds from 0.5 to 0.95, representing overall detection robustness). Further analysis was conducted using the F1-Confidence Curve to determine the optimal confidence threshold that maximizes the balance between Precision and Recall. The training convergence was monitored via the Validation Loss Curves. The model contains 225 layers and 3,006,038 fused parameters.

4. # Results and discussion

To evaluate the convergence and stability of our YOLOv8n model, we tracked multiple loss components across 50 epochs via TensorBoard. These included the primary detection losses: the bounding box loss (Box Loss), the classification loss (Cls Loss), and the Distribution Focal Loss (DFL Loss). For visualization purposes, we monitored both the training and validation loss plots to confirm smooth minimization and prevent overfitting. The final detection performance was subsequently measured using Mean Average Precision (mAP) and validated against the F1-Confidence Curve to determine the optimal deployment threshold.

   2. ## *Model Performance and Evaluation Metrics*

![][image23]

7. F1–Confidence Curve for YOLOv8 Fire and Smoke Detection Model

The figure presents the variation in F1 score with respect to the confidence threshold for fire, smoke, and all classes combined. The combined curve achieves a peak F1 score of approximately 0.80 at a confidence threshold of 0.36, indicating an optimal balance between precision and recall. The smoke class consistently attains higher F1 values than the fire class, suggesting that smoke is detected more reliably across confidence levels. At very high confidence thresholds, the F1 score drops sharply due to reduced recall, highlighting the importance of selecting an appropriate confidence threshold for real-time fire and smoke detection.

![][image24]

8. Precision–Recall Curve

The Precision–Recall curve illustrates the trade-off between precision and recall for the fire and smoke classes, as well as for all classes combined. The smoke class achieves a high average precision of 0.940, indicating strong detection reliability with minimal false positives across most recall levels. In contrast, the fire class records a lower average precision of 0.734, suggesting greater variability and a higher likelihood of missed detections or false alarms, particularly at higher recall values. The combined performance yields an overall mAP@0.5 of 0.837, demonstrating that the model performs effectively in detecting fire and smoke. The sharper decline in precision for the fire class at higher recall highlights the challenge of accurately detecting flames under varying conditions, emphasizing the need for diverse training data and careful threshold selection for real-time deployment.

![][image25]

9. Recall–Confidence Curve

This figure demonstrates how recall varies as the confidence threshold increases for fire, smoke, and all detected classes. At low confidence values, the model achieves high recall, with an overall recall of approximately 0.94, indicating that most fire and smoke instances are successfully detected. As the confidence threshold rises, recall gradually decreases, reflecting the model’s increasing strictness in accepting detections. The smoke class consistently maintains higher recall than the fire class across most confidence levels, suggesting that smoke features are more reliably captured by the model. The sharp decline near high confidence thresholds highlights the trade-off between reducing false positives and maintaining detection coverage, which is critical for real-time fire monitoring applications.

![][image26]

10. Confusion Matrix

The Confusion Matrix provides a fine-grained analysis of the model's classification accuracy, revealing the counts of correct and incorrect predictions across the fire, smoke, and background categories. The matrix confirms the model's high capability to distinguish between the two primary object classes, with only 14 true fire instances being misclassified as smoke and only 3 true smoke instances being misclassified as fire. The largest true positive counts are for smoke (3,680) and fire (2,637). However, the matrix highlights two main areas for improvement: firstly, a significant number of true fire (953) and true smoke (390) instances are missed and incorrectly predicted as background (False Negatives), which directly limits the model's Recall. Secondly, the largest single error is the prediction of 1,152 true background instances as fire (False Positives), severely impacting the Precision, especially for the 'fire' class. In summary, while class separability is excellent, future optimization should focus on reducing both the False Negatives (improving detection coverage) and the high rate of False Positives (reducing false alarms from the background).

11. Real-Time Detection Frame Example

The figure, titled "Real-Time Detection Frame Example", presents a visual snapshot of the YOLOv8 model's performance on an unseen frame, showcasing its ability to localize and classify fire and smoke in a complex, real-world scenario, likely from a drone or aerial perspective. The visualization confirms the model's fundamental capability for both detection and classification, as evidenced by the multiple green bounding boxes and corresponding class labels ("fire" or "smoke") overlaid on the image. Overall, this visualization serves as compelling qualitative proof that the YOLOv8 system is functional and capable of providing real-time, actionable intelligence by accurately pinpointing the locations of both fire and smoke in an operational setting, thereby supporting the quantitative metrics of high precision and mAP observed during training.

5. ## *Data Imbalance Observation*

Analysis across the evaluation metrics strongly suggests the presence of a data imbalance in the training data, primarily affecting the 'fire' class. The F1-Confidence Curve revealed a significant performance disparity, with the 'smoke' class achieving an optimal F1-score near 0.90, notably higher than the 'fire' class at 0.70. This gap indicates that the model is learning more robust features for smoke detection. Furthermore, the Confusion Matrix reinforced this imbalance by showing disproportionately high error rates for 'fire': the model generated 1,152 False Positives (misclassifying background as fire) and 953 False Negatives (missing true fire instances), numbers significantly higher than the corresponding errors for the 'smoke' class. These elevated errors point to an insufficient variety or quantity of 'fire' samples, leading the model to be either too aggressive in predicting fire (lowering Precision) or too conservative (lowering Recall). Therefore, addressing the underrepresentation or lack of diversity of the 'fire' class in the dataset is a critical next step for improving overall system reliability.

6. # Conclusion

	In this project, we implemented and trained a YOLOv8-based fire and smoke detection model capable of operating on both images and real-time video streams. Our system leverages modern one-stage object detection techniques to localize fire and smoke regions with high spatial accuracy. YOLOv8 incorporates advanced architectural features—such as anchor-free detection, decoupled heads, and rich data augmentation—which allowed our model to converge stably during training and generalize effectively across a wide range of fire scenarios.

After training on approximately 4,000 labeled images of fire and smoke, the model demonstrated strong performance in terms of precision, recall, and mAP, along with fast inference speeds suitable for real-time applications. Qualitative results further confirmed the model’s ability to detect fires of varying sizes, intensities, and environmental conditions, even in scenes with complex backgrounds or partially obscured smoke. These findings suggest that YOLOv8 provides a promising foundation for building practical wildfire detection systems.

However, several limitations remain. The dataset exhibits some imbalance between fire, smoke, and background categories, which may impact detection robustness in underrepresented conditions. Additionally, the model occasionally struggles in scenes with dense smoke, low-light environments, or extremely small fire regions. Future work should explore expanding the dataset with more diverse fire scenarios, particularly nighttime imagery and heavier smoke coverage. Additional improvements may include integrating thermal or infrared modalities, optimizing the model for deployment on edge-computing devices, and refining the inference pipeline to reduce false positives.

Long-term extensions could involve deploying the model on drone platforms, incorporating temporal tracking for continuous monitoring, and combining YOLOv8 with environmental sensor data to enhance reliability in early wildfire detection systems. All work, including code, dataset configurations, and training scripts, will be made available to support further research in real-time fire and smoke detection. The project’s work and source code will be publicly available. [Project](https://github.com/CPP-F25-CS5190-Final/CS5190-final-prototype)
